<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY DIGEST: SPRING VALLEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A University City man and a woman described as his transient companion were 
arrested early Friday in Spring Valley on suspicion of running a 
methamphetamine manufacturing lab out of a motor home, which contained 1 1/2 
pounds of the drug, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
Frank C. Puente, 34, and Deborah Terlaje, 24, were booked into County Jail on 
suspicion of manufacturing the drug and of being under its influence, said a 
spokesman for the San Diego County Sheriff's Department. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Richard Bolter from the Lemon Grove substation arrested the two after 
responding to a citizen's complaint about 12:30 a.m. that a small motor home 
was "driving up and down" the 1600 block of Grand Avenue in Spring Valley, the 
spokesman said. Bolter pulled the driver over and reportedly smelled ether 
emanating from inside the vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
Narcotics Task Force agents confiscated the motor home, deputies said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
