<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY DIGEST: IRVINE; 
</P>
<P>
CALTRANS, MEASURE M REPRESENTED AT FORUM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Transportation in Orange County's Future" will be discussed by slow-growth 
activist Norm Grossman and the California Department of Transportation's Orange 
County director, Keith McKean, at a Town Hall forum on Wednesday in Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
Grossman, a supporter of Measure M, the proposed county half-cent sales tax for 
highway and transit projects and a leader in the campaign on behalf of last 
year's unsuccessful slow-growth ballot initiative, currently serves as first 
vice president of the Orange County Foundation for Consensus in Transportation, 
a coalition of business executives and community activists. 
</P>
<P>
Town Hall officials said Grossman will explain "how your personal 
transportation scenarios can help shape the future of transportation in Orange 
County." 
</P>
<P>
McKean has been asked to address the question, "What has Caltrans done for us 
lately?" 
</P>
<P>
The luncheon forum will be held at noon at the Airporter Inn, 18700 MacArthur 
Blvd. 
</P>
<P>
Additional information is available from Carol Starcevic at (213) 628-8141. 
</P>
<P>
Town Hall of California is a volunteer, nonprofit organization that invites 
prominent activists and decision makers to air their views at luncheons held 
throughout the year. 
</P>
