<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: HOTELS/TOURISM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Mary Ann Galante, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Radisson Plaza Hotel in Irvine has named two top executives who will 
oversee operations when the hotel reopens later this year. 
</P>
<P>
Aref Haffar of Corona del Mar has been named general manager, in charge of 
overseeing the hotel's management and executive staff. He was vice president of 
the western division for Servico, one of the country's largest hotel owners and 
operators. 
</P>
<P>
Sher L. Pasquini has been named resident manager, overseeing rooms divisions, 
operations, budget and guest services. She has worked in management positions 
with the Hyatt Hotel Corp. and was resident manager for the Sheraton Atlanta 
Airport Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
The appointments come three months after the 293-room hotel was bought by a 
group of Orange County investors for $26 million in late June. At the time of 
the purchase, the property was a closed, bankrupt Registry Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
GMY Investment Co., a Newport Beach limited partnership of five investors, 
bought the hotel from Homestead Savings &amp; Loan. The group has been engaged 
in a multimillion-dollar renovation and has scheduled a reopening for November. 
</P>
<P>
The Registry fell on hard times as a result of intense competition in the 
airport area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
